snippet.textDisplay:
Id like to share my sleep deprivation story:
As a teen I was put in a behavioral hospital. It screwed me up so much, when I got discharged, I kept having nightmares about the hospital. So, I stayed up. I stayed awake for 4 days straight. I remember being confused a lot. I was shaking, i didnt want to eat. On the 4th night, I thought someone was watching me through the door. As i laid in my bed, now desperate to fall asleep again (i had stayed up 2 days, and i wanted to sleep again) i suddenly heard the sound of an air compressor going off. And suddenly, i felt like someone had smashed my ribs in. I thought the fan fell on top of me. I opened my eyes, and looked around. Everything was silent, the fan on the ceiling. This happened 4 times that night, not stopping until 5 or 6 AM on my 5th day. I finally passed out on my 5th day. To this day, i still get random electric shocks down my neck that are so bad I begged my mom to drive me to the hospital. No one knows what these shocks are.

snippet.textDisplay:
The bangungot is a filipino term that describes nightmares that restricts you to move your body using your consciousness. This is usually due from over fatigue, and distress.

Most say that if you don't want to experience bangungot, you must not sleep straight and facing up, you can't sleep right after eating, and if you're exhausted and in need of sleep, try relaxing before sleeping.
snippet.textOriginal:
The bangungot is a filipino term that describes nightmares that restricts you to move your body using your consciousness. This is usually due from over fatigue, and distress.
